Web-Scraping XBox Games

Import BeautifulSoap

BeautifulSoap to extract and work with HTML and XML data.

url of the website: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Xbox_games

In[]:
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
import requests

url = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Xbox_games"
r = requests.get(url)
soup = BeautifulSoup(r.content, "html.parser")
print(soup.prettify())

      <div aria-labelledby="firstHeading" class="vector-body" data-mw-ve-target-container="" id="bodyContent">
       <div class="vector-body-before-content">
        <div class="mw-indicators">
        </div>
        <div class="noprint" id="siteSub">
         From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
        </div>
       </div>
       <div id="contentSub">
        <div id="mw-content-subtitle">
        </div>
       </div>
       <div class="mw-body-content" id="mw-content-text">
        <div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" dir="ltr" lang="en">
         <p class="mw-empty-elt">
         </p>
         <figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb">
          <a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Xbox-console.jpg">
           <img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="2620" data-file-width="5700" decoding="async" height="118" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Xbox-console.jpg/256px-Xbox-console.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Xbox-console.jpg/384px-Xbox-console.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/43/Xbox-console.jpg/512px-Xbox-console.jpg 2x" width="256"/>
          </a>
          <figcaption>
           The Xbox
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
         <figure typeof="mw:File/Thumb">
          <a class="mw-file-description" href="/wiki/File:Xbox_original_banner.jpg">
           <img class="mw-file-element" data-file-height="52" data-file-width="350" decoding="async" height="38" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/05/Xbox_original_banner.jpg/256px-Xbox_original_banner.jpg" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/05/Xbox_original_banner.jpg 1.5x" width="256"/>
          </a>
          <figcaption>
           Official Xbox Banner used on games exclusive to Xbox
          </figcaption>
         </figure>
         <p>
          The
          <b>
           <a href="/wiki/Xbox_(console)" title="Xbox (console)">
            Xbox
           </a>
          </b>
          is
          <a href="/wiki/Microsoft" title="Microsoft">
           Microsoft
          </a>
          's first home
          <a href="/wiki/Video_game_console" title="Video game console">
           video game console
          </a>
          , released during the
          <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/History_of_video_game_consoles_(sixth_generation)" title="History of video game consoles (sixth generation)">
           sixth generation of video games
          </a>
          . There are a total of
          <i>
           <b>
            988
           </b>
          </i>
          <sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-1">
           <a href="#cite_note-1">
            [a]
           </a>
          </sup>
          titles on this list. This list does not include
          <a href="/wiki/Xbox_Live_Arcade" title="Xbox Live Arcade">
           Xbox Live Arcade
          </a>
          games, demos, or bonus discs. For games that were announced or revealed to be in development for the original Xbox, but never released, see the
          <a href="/wiki/List_of_cancelled_Xbox_games" title="List of cancelled Xbox games">
           list of cancelled Xbox games
          </a>
          .
         </p>
         <p>
          For a chronological list, click the sort button in any of the available region's column. Games dated November 15, 2001 (NA), February 22, 2002 (JP), and March 14, 2002 (PAL) are launch titles of each region respectively.
         </p>
         <h2>
          <span class="mw-headline" id="Games">
           Games
          </span>
          <span class="mw-editsection">
           <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
            [
           </span>
           <a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_Xbox_games&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Games">
            <span>
             edit
            </span>
           </a>
           <span class="mw-editsection-bracket">
            ]
           </span>
          </span>
         </h2>

Finding all the Titles for the columns of the table

In[]:
world_title = games_list[0].find_all("th")

world_title
Out[]:
[<th rowspan="2" style="width:25%;">Title
 </th>,
 <th rowspan="2" style="width:14%;">Developer(s)
 </th>,
 <th rowspan="2" style="width:14%;">Publisher(s)
 </th>,
 <th colspan="3" style="width:14%;">Release date
 </th>,
 <th><abbr title="PAL regions, which include Europe and Australasia">PAL</abbr>
 </th>,
 <th><abbr title="Japan">JP</abbr>
 </th>,
 <th><abbr title="North America">NA</abbr>
 </th>]

Using .text to extract the text from the titles.

Using strip() to remove the white spaces

In[]:
world_table_titles = [title.text.strip() for title in world_title]

print(world_table_titles)

['Title', 'Developer(s)', 'Publisher(s)', 'Release date', 'PAL', 'JP', 'NA']

Import Pandas

Use pandas to work with dataframes.

Using pandas to store the titles data in a dataframe df.

In[]:
import pandas as pd

df = pd.DataFrame(columns = world_table_titles)

df
Out[]:
Title Developer(s) Publisher(s) Release date PAL JP NA

Getting all Row data from the source site.

column_data = games_list[0].find_all("tr")

print(column_data)

for row in column_data[2:]:
    row_data = row.find_all("td")
    individual_row_data = [data.text.strip() for data in row_data]
    print(individual_row_data)

In[]:
df = pd.DataFrame(columns = world_table_titles)
for col in df.columns:
    if 'Release date' in col:
        del df[col]

Iterate over the rows and store the data in the dataframe.

Also, calculate the length of the dataframe and assign the data to the dataframe by using .loc method.

In[]:
for row in column_data[2:]:
    row_data = row.find_all("td")
    individual_row_data = [data.text.strip() for data in row_data]
    
    length = len(df)
    df.loc[length] = individual_row_data
    
df
